Project Intoduction:

DDSAnalytics is an analytics company that specializes in talent management solutions for Fortune 100 companies. Talent management is defined as the iterative process of developing and retaining employees. It may include workforce planning, employee training programs, identifying high-potential employees and reducing/preventing voluntary employee turnover (attrition). To gain a competitive edge over its competition, DDSAnalytics is planning to leverage data science for talent management

The goal of this project is for DDSAnalytics team is: 1. To provide Attition analysis, 2. Identify to 3 reasons for Attition. 4. Attition prediction model (with sensitivity and specificity > 60%) 5. Monthly salary prediction model to Frito Lay company with RMSE > $3000.

Executive Summary:

The data provided by Frito Lay company contains information of 870 employees with 35 features. Current attrition rate based on the data provided is 16%

Attrition by Departments: Sales Department with highest Attrition of 22% Research and Development department with lowest attrition of 13% Human Resources Department attrition rate is 17%

Job Role Attrition : The highest Attrition is of Sales representatives of 45% The lowest Attrition is of Research Director 0f under 2%

Top 3 Factors which lead to Attrition: 1. Work Environment: Job Involvement 46% attrition Overtime 31% attrition Work Life Balance 35% attrition Environment satisfaction 24% attrition low Job Satisfaction 21% attrition 2. Money Monthly Income under 2700 31% attrition Stock Options 25% attrition 3. Tenure + Age and Marital status 38% of employees with under 4 total years tend to leave 34% of employees with under 2 years in the current role leave Over 20% of employees who are less than 3 years with the current manager tend to leave. 26% of Single employees leave the company
30% of employees under 27 years old tend to leave company

Recommendations:

  1. Add high potential employees to the Stock option plans
  2. Improve working environments Include fun events Improve work-life balance
  3. More engagement with employees with lower tenure Explain promotion options Show career possibilities

From the data exploration analysis: 1. We find strong correlation between monthly income and Working years - pearson correlation 0.78 2. Monthly income VS Total Years at the Company - we find gradual increase in monthly income for all 3 departments also we see significant jump in monthly salary for Human department after ~15 years in the company 3. Higher monthly income is for the management Roles Sales Representatives have the lowest income with not that high variance – huge attrition 4. Human Resources have the Best Work Life Balance Research Scientists have the lowest Work Life Balance

Prediction Models:
1. Attrition Prediction Models - we selected Logistic Regression with forward algorithm for feature selection as the best performer 2. Monthly Income Prediction Models - LASSO was the best performer

##Atrition Analysis # # ################################################################################

data.analysis <- CaseStudy2_Data_clean

PopabilityDistributionGraph <- function(col_name){
  
  title <- paste('Percentage of Attrition for ', col_name)  
  
  data.analysis%>%ggplot(aes(data.analysis[[col_name]], fill= Attrition)) +
    geom_bar(aes(y=(..count..)/sum(..count..)), color='black',position="fill")+
    ggtitle(label=title) +  xlab(col_name) + 
    ylab('Percentage') #+coord_flip()
  
}



AnalysisBarPlot <- function(col_name){
  title <- paste('Distribution for ', col_name)  
  CaseStudy2_Data_clean %>% ggplot( aes(CaseStudy2_Data_clean[[col_name]])) +  geom_bar()+
    ggtitle(label=title) +  xlab(col_name) 
}

    MaritalStatus + JobSatisfaction + DistanceFromHome + EnvironmentSatisfaction +

    WorkLifeBalance + NumCompaniesWorked + Age + BusinessTravel + 
    TrainingTimesLastYear + HourlyRate + TotalWorkingYears +

    PerformanceRating + PercentSalaryHike + EducationField, family = binomial(link = "logit"), 
    data = train.Tree)
